An index longer than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index finger longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before age 60," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
In this way, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining with genetic risk or other stressful factors such as familial antecedents, Eeles added.
During the 1994-2009 period she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
For those who had the index longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60 the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - shows in particular different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that testosterone is exactly what helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that he does not seem to believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "fully demonstrated."
