Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Department of Justice prosecutors dropped criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case related to an assistant in an old campaign and his efforts to get lobbying work for the wife's husband, announced on Wednesday the Senator's lawyers.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican of Nevada, who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made the national headlines last year and undermined his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The Senator could still be subject to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer under investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice that there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in the New York Times in October 2009, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative lobbying work to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the Senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer in an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was barred for one year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends prior to the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called lobby door ban.
According to the evidence that was made public, "there seems to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to violate and a substantial violation of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington-based lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks in its Public Integrity Section, including the decisions taken last year to drop the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens accused of failing to prosecute.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Director General for Citizens' Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's senior counsel, stated in an interview that he had received a telephone call on Monday from a Department of Justice prosecutor and a follow-up the following day, telling him that the Department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with the prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated on Wednesday in a statement, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents in Hampton violated federal election law.
The Election Commission stated that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a prominent Nevada company that has long supported the Senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's Chief of Staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Ministry of the Interior on a matter in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Transportation Secretary to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, stated that the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and terminate its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
Cheshire's call to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were tapping away in the rows of the courtroom.
They sent horrifying testimonials every minute via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said that there were over 140,000 messages about the rape trial and the children attached to their bed in a house that was set on fire.
Thursday, the largely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was found guilty of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to culminate in an official end to the death penalty imposed by the judge, which was passed by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that sketches appeal arguments that could occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reports on the trial - as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists - created a "circus atmosphere," a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with inflammatory details that the jury was badly influenced by public passions.
The request could lead the appellate judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
"I have experienced this during this trial; I think there is a real danger that the introduction of new technologies into courtrooms is undermining human rights to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Bleue of the Superior Court of State, laconically rejected the claims in last week's judgement, claiming that the media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was motivated by passion.
But that does not seem to be the last word on the issue.
Appeal courts have recognized for decades that media coverage of well-known cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark judgment of 1966, the United States Supreme Court quashed the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, arguing in his decision that there was a "carnival atmosphere at trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television show and the film "The fugitive."
Some lawyers have stated that the appellate courts seized to review Mr. Hayes's conviction half a century later may be curious given the argument that new rules might be necessary to manage courtroom communications, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is a general reason to worry about the impact of new media" in large trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily applied.
Professor Donohue stated that some appellate judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
The case of Twitter is only one of many described by Mr. Hayes' lawyers, which can be discussed for years; this delays execution.
Defence counsel also allege, for example, that Mr. Hayes would have suffered harm when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them macabre photos of criminal scenes during the selection of the jury.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defence lawyers argue that they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the juror, who had been criticized before the prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure on a verdict by making the unusual decision to have the jury deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for the office of governor and the Senate of the United States.
They maintained that the computer media were constantly stirring the flames of the emotion of the case.
"The daily hustle of media tweets, cameras and journalists outside the courthouse," the lawyers wrote, "looked nothing like what had been seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even on a national scale."
Their focus on Twitter coverage is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists stated that the assertion that snapshots were more inflammatory than press releases delivered more slowly was a Luddist view that would impoverish the Court's policy of media coverage of future trials.
However, some lawyers stated that courts of appeal were often drawn to arguments that social and technological changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers insist on this claim.
In their case, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that reversed Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of the media coverage of the trial and stated that they would invoke the need for new rules for the new media.
"This case," they wrote, "represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility bring the cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a forerunner sign of genuine forward bipartite cooperation or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and Congress leaders did not produce any breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the "lame duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the president's deficit committee was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide, but still divides the membership.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of trial and trial with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too profound to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxation, expenditure, health care or rights, both sides remain miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
The elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade away.
That's good. "
On certain issues, notably those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise could be reached on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because the Republicans could not afford to give the impression that they were in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on "lame duck," with the ratification of the New START Pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "blade duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Committee, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their view, have imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had difficulty reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group, suggesting that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as the Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; then be followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want both parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Whoever is judged to be in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility displayed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will be needed on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Disclosed U.S. documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and brings some of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, reported the US Embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of life in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the "vertical power" - takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memorandum, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been expurged.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
