Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with low-quality decepted concrete walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School referred to the man who had built it, the last Khmer Rouge chief, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader, and he cared about his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwest Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to face publicly the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches Khmer Rouge history to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led by the United Nations, handed down its first sentence concerning a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former leader of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch," to 35 years in prison.
In the face of these developments, anxiety has increased among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the United Pol Pot government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they launched an uprising that lasted until the last of the movements arrived in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrillas from their base in the western mountains of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a suite in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Hangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have fallen into black poverty, common to the rural areas of Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic of the movement.
Although some elite Khmer Rouge officers have held their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down arms, they are unskilled farmers of low rank and file.
"These people benefited from very little follow-up after the capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are imbibed with the Utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in a context where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to support ourselves. "
The current Khmer Rouge Court has also caused concern here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, start the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to try the senior leaders and the main perpetrators of the crimes, but it did not say whether it continued beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm Anlong Veng's fears.
The latest media speculation turned to Im Chaem, 64 years old, former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the rule of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers were reportedly killed.
Recently, during a torrid evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the field near his wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there is more prosecution, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Yuk Chhang, from the documentation center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect broken pieces," he says.
"We have to put these pieces together so we can understand."
The centre produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A 75-page history of Democratic Kampuchea."
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history textbooks of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the ties of the city to the regime.
19-year-old Touch Valeak, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new manual helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he came home with the book to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They are suspicious because they don't know exactly how many people the court will pursue."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge keep a powerful lure here.
In the heights of the mountains of Hangrek, a path, invaded by weeds and sprinkled with plastic bags, leads to a black soot rectangle, covered with a rusty sheet roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Noom Sothea, 31 years old, a roadside mobile phone saleswoman, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many inhabitants go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she planned to walk to the last resting place in Pol Pot where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing luck.
