This is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with goals far away from the high motorist competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to create assembly chains for manufacturing plants all over the world, power stations, high precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before constructing it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 plant allowed Red Bull to create and execute "in a few hours, almost in real time," the changes, changes and improvements detected during races and trials.
