In Red Bull's team, 180 young professionals of high quality are working today, who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project any kind of modifications to the cars.
Siemens' manager explained that PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull's cars except the engine, which is the exclusive responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be made from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced high-tech laser and autoclave production systems.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological development there is the $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend as a limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech plant to create and produce its cars in a locality 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret."
The staff for this assignment consists of 580 people, including two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's Formula One hero, no doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
