Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team coach, José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved with two games.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not more common in the football world.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the related case owes to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of Real Madrid's entity (which in its hymn displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to its dilated history of Histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulation, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit a fraud of law; for, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sporting regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sportsmanship.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the offending players team from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret in order to try to avoid punishment, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible in order to receive the penalisation of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and they willingly accepted the sanction.
Another question is the type of benefit that offenders obtain from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that we do not put the rival at a disadvantage and we do not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without boxes that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second cycle of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladder, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which is still part of the strategic decision-making that promotes the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not operate to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without defeating the penalty or fleeing that penalty.
Even though the boundary between the genius and the fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
