A global plan to renovate lighting
Yesterday in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that is almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if incandescent light bulbs that still monopolize 50-70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent light bulbs or, better, light emitting diode (LED) light bulbs, most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilise by 2020 the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the energy requirement is reduced by another two times.
The average length of compact fluorescent bulbs is 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as that launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they don't contain mercury.
A number of specialists have shown reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers implement instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and 8 million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost it 2.5 billion.
