Hackers Vengeance and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals itself as an apparent scandal, a scandal which only appears to be a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only bring back what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those that Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinister caricatural profile had long been for cabaret artists subject to sketch.
The rule that secret records should only be composed of known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who commit themselves to occultism only believe in what they already know, and who reconfirm what they had already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same goes for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Libération), who only considers as true what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
Then why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state could call or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises of representation, have turned into espionage centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, public repetition violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims into crisis as much as the "executioners."
But let's get to the deep nature of what happened.
In the days of Orwell, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secrecy, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any reserved information - that would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to expect to be able to maintain confidential relationships over the telephone.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state travelled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I am well aware that for the time being my forecast is science fiction and is therefore romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly along uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be stored as a single copy in locked drawers: in the background, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephone).
The videocassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow us to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travel it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not unusual, therefore, that the policy and communication techniques should be returned to the horse-drawn cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France is fooling its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to look at the implementation of the promises of fast-start and early-stage financing made by developed countries.
And the big French dudes are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU took the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the actions of its member states, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency exercise is appreciated and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to meet its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional," in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it is adding $150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1 €loan is equivalent to 1 €.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission mitigation projects that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (equivalent to an interest rate) should be counted against its commitments.
But France has no intention of making such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of grants (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other cases) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it can make it appear that it is spending 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early financing chapter is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting system for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): the question of "additionality" or how loans should be accounted for will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
